title: Laser Assisted Cold Spray of Aluminum Alloy 6061: Experimental Results

extractedText.notes: Control condition (TS-0kW-T): Cold spray deposition of Al6061 powder on an Al6061-T6 substrate without laser assistance or extra heating, resulting in low ultimate tensile strength and very low elongation.

Intermediate condition (TS-3kW-H): Laser-assisted cold spray using 3 kW laser power with substrate heating (hotplate), yielding a marked increase in tensile strength compared to the control, with moderate deposit softening.

Enhanced condition (TS-5kW-H): Laser-assisted cold spray with 5 kW laser power and hotplate backing, producing a high spray spot temperature (~455°C) that causes significant intersplat bonding, deposit softening, and marked improvements in both tensile strength and ductility.

title: Impact of Ultrasonic Nanocrystal Surface Modification on the Corrosion Behavior of Cold Sprayed and Additive Friction Stir Deposited 304L Austenitic Stainless Steel

extractedText.notes: As‐deposited cold‐sprayed 304L SS coating was produced by depositing 304L SS powder (using He as the propellant at a pressure of about 600 (unit not provided) and a gas temperature of ~350°C) onto a 304L SS substrate. The resulting coating had a thickness of 3 mm (with area ~27×34 mm) and a near–surface nano–hardness of approximately 594 HV. Corrosion testing (CPP in 3.5 wt.% NaCl) showed a high degree of susceptibility (DOS ~12.1%) and a high corrosion rate (~0.235 mpy), with no clear stable pitting potential observed.

As–deposited Laser Assisted Cold Spray (LACS) 304L SS coating was made by depositing 304L SS powder onto a 304L SS substrate using a cold spray process assisted by laser preheating (laser heat ~950°C) with other parameters similar to the CS process (pressure ~600, base temperature ~350°C). The coating had the same thickness (3 mm, area ~27×34 mm) but its average near–surface hardness was about 378 HV. In corrosion tests, the as–deposited LACS coating showed a higher degree of susceptibility (DOS ~19.7%)—in part due to the formation of an inhomogeneous oxide film. (Polishing of LACS coatings greatly improves DOS.)
